To stezothewhitenegro...I would reply to you, but it appears you may have 
turned off the option to allow people to reply..shame...but anyway , ..your 
statement is a really silly one..you are more or less saying that "thanks 
to the internet" the public can get proof of some mystical creature out to 
the world..and that scientists and the like are just there to cover this 
stuff up...
Thanks to the internet, every nut with a few bucks can get his or her crazy 
assed theories out to the world, and  they may even make websites that some 
other nutjobs can proclaim is "proof" of whatever fantastic claims they may 
have... 
Why is the thought that this is footage of something perfectly normal seem 
so far fetched to folks like yourself? Is your everyday life boring to the 
extreme that you must entertain these notions to feel more pertinent and 
relevant? I am curious...is the thought that this may be a poor Orca that 
has found itself in the mouth of a river or a harbour, ahead of a tsunami 
not a wondrous enough thing, that it has to be made out to be some 
un-explainable beast? Frankly I have given a lot of thought as of late to 
what life was like before the WWW...and I gotta say I preferred it over the 
nonsense I see showcased online today..We had the opportunity to take this 
great invention and use it to revolutionize the world of communication, to 
make life better for people in third world countries and to offer an 
invaluable tool to healthcare workers and people in general...and what did 
we do with it? We dumped a bunch of porn into it...gave access to mothers 
and aunts all over the world to post their recipes and pictures of their 
grandkids..and gave spammers and online crooks a tool to make life 
miserable..oh..and it became fertile ground for mentally unstable, 
miscreants to post their broken thoughts about every bit of their 
lives..whether we want it or not! Oh..and cats..lots of pictures of cats...﻿

+Michael Quindlen I know it...but..it makes me wonder where these people
